<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-448-731  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 448 731.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  August 22 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Control Data to sell Russia most powerful computer to date. (CYBER960)</TITLE><AUTHOR>McMullen, Barbara E.; McMullen, John F.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Control Data Corp. (export-import trade).andO;Ticker:    CDA.andO;Product:   Control Data Cyber 960 (Mainframe computer) (export-import trade).andO;Topic:     Computer industrySoviet UnionExportCommerce.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>CONTROL DATA TO SELL RUSSIA MOST POWERFUL COMPUTER TO DATE MINNEAPOLIS,MINNESOTA, U.S.A., 1990 AUG 22 (NB) -- Control Data Corporation has announcedthat U.S.andP;  Department of Commerce has granted the company an export licenseto ship six CYBER 960 mainframe computers to the Soviet Union.andM;Control Data states that the computers to be shipped beginning in Septemberare the most powerful ever shipped to the Soviet Union from the West.andP;  Thesale is valued at $32 million.andM;The computers were ordered by the Soviet Research and Development Instituteof Power Engineering and will be used to analyze safety factors in theoperation of civilian Soviet nuclear power reactors over a wide range ofconditions.andP;  The Soviet Union's civilian nuclear power program is one of thelargest in the world with approximately 50 plants in operation.andM;Last year half of the Soviet Union's nuclear-generated electricity wasproduced by plants designed by the institute that has ordered the ControlData computers.andM;During Soviet President Gorbachev's visit to the United States in June, heattended a Control Data demonstration of the CYBER 960 computers.andP;  At thattime, he spoke of the Soviet Union's commitment to increased safety fornuclear power plants and spoke on the need for greater technological andcommercial cooperation between the United States and the Soviet Union in thisarea.andM;Control Data applied for the export license last November and announced theSoviet order on Dec. 12, 1989.andP;  As part of the process, the company workedwith the U.S.andP;  Departments of Commerce, State, Defense and Energy to developsafeguards that the computers will be dedicated to safety analysis ofcivilian nuclear reactors.andP;  The Coordinating Committee on Multilateral ExportControls (COCOM) also approved the shipment.andM;Commenting on the process that led to the granting of government approval,Jim Ousley, president of Control Data's computer business, said, &quot;Thisconcludes the export license process Control Data initiated almost a yearago.andP;  But it marks the beginning of a new level of cooperation between theSoviet Union and United States on issues that affect people worldwide -- inthis case, the safe operation of nuclear power plants.&quot;andM;(Barbara E. McMullen andamp; John F. McMullen/19900822/Press Contact: ThomasCharland, Control Data, 612-853-6394)</TEXT></DOC>